> How's this for a dose of sour power? Here, we're showing you how to make sweet and sour from
> scratch. That's right, we're breaking down the mystery sauce into something made from real
> ingredients and zhooshing it up with fresh ginger and garlic. It gets tossed with shrimp,
> bell peppers, and snow peas for a meal that's far more memorable than anything you'd get
> from your delivery joint.

Wash and dry all produce. Bring 2⅔ cups water to a boil in a #medium pot{}. Trim any tough
stems from @snow peas{8%oz}. Mince or grate @garlic{2%clove}. Core, seed, and remove white
ribs from @red bell pepper{1}, then chop into bite-sized pieces. Peel and mince
@ginger{1%thumb}.

Once water boils, add @jasmine rice{1.5%cup} to #pot, cover, and reduce to a simmer. Cook
until tender, ~{15-20%minutes}. Remove from heat and keep covered.

Whisk together @soy sauce{2%unit}, @white wine vinegar{2%tablespoon},
@ketchup{1%unit}, @sugar{2%teaspoon}, @cornstarch{2%teaspoon}, and ¾ cup water in a
#small bowl{} until there are no more lumps.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over high heat. Add
bell pepper and snow peas. Cook until just starting to brown, about ~{3%minutes},
stirring constantly. Toss in garlic, ginger, and @shrimp{16%ounce} and cook until shrimp
are starting to turn pink, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add sauce to pan, tossing to coat veggies and shrimp. Let it come to a boil, then cook
until thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}. Divide between plates and top with stir-fry. Tear
@cilantro{¼%ounce} leaves from stems. Garnish plates with cilantro (to taste) and
@cashew pieces{1%ounce}.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste.